      -------------------------------------------------------------------
       Compile-time configuration macros (include/configuration.h)
      -------------------------------------------------------------------


1. Overview
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The header include/configuration.h defines compile-time macros that control the
library's threading model, context propagation strategy, provider architecture,
and optional validation.  The macros under the OTELC_USER_CONFIG guard can be
overridden by defining OTELC_USER_CONFIG before the header is included and
supplying a fully custom set of definitions.

When OTELC_USER_CONFIG is not defined, the following defaults apply:

  Macro                                Default
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  OTELC_USE_THREAD_SHARED_HANDLE       defined
  OTELC_USE_STATIC_HANDLE              undefined
  OTELC_USE_COMPOSITE_PROPAGATOR       defined
  OTELC_USE_MULTIPLE_PROCESSORS        defined
  OTELC_USE_RUNTIME_CONTEXT            undefined

One additional macro, OTELC_USE_INSTRUMENT_VALIDATOR, is defined outside the
OTELC_USER_CONFIG block and is always undefined.


2. OTELC_USE_THREAD_SHARED_HANDLE
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Default: defined.

Selects between a shared-handle model and a thread-local model for span and
span context storage.

When defined, span and span context handles are stored in global structures
shared across all threads.  Each structure is a sharded map with 64
independently-locked shards.  Every span operation (lookup, insert, erase)
acquires the per-shard mutex for the shard selected by the handle's index.
The THREAD_LOCAL macro expands to nothing, and OTEL_HANDLE_SHARED is true.

When undefined, span and span context handles are thread-local.  Each thread
owns its own handle map, and no locking is needed.  The THREAD_LOCAL macro
expands to the thread_local keyword, OTEL_HANDLE_SHARED is false, and
OTEL_LOCK_TRACER() compiles to a no-op.

The shared-handle model is required for applications where one thread may
access spans created by another (e.g. a span started on an accept thread and
ended on a worker thread).  The thread-local model eliminates all lock overhead
but restricts each span to the thread that created it.


3. OTELC_USE_STATIC_HANDLE
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Default: undefined.

Selects between statically allocated and dynamically allocated handle maps.

When defined, handle maps are declared as static (or thread-local) objects
that the C++ runtime constructs automatically.  The OTEL_HANDLE(h, m) macro
expands to ((h).m), accessing the handle via the dot operator.  The
otel_tracer_handle_init() function is compiled out entirely because the
handles already exist.

When undefined, handle maps are declared as pointers initialized to nullptr.
The OTEL_HANDLE(h, m) macro expands to ((h)->m), accessing the handle via
the arrow operator.  The otel_tracer_handle_init() function allocates both
otel_span and otel_span_context handle maps on first use via new(std::nothrow),
and is called from otel_tracer_start_span_with_options() and
otel_tracer_extract_*() before any handle access.

The dynamic model avoids constructing handle maps for threads that never create
spans.  The static model avoids the null-pointer check and the allocation call
on first use, at the cost of constructing the handle map unconditionally.


4. OTELC_USE_COMPOSITE_PROPAGATOR
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Default: defined.

Selects between a composite propagator that handles both trace context and
baggage, and an HTTP-only propagator that requires separate baggage handling.

When defined, the tracer's start() function creates an HttpTraceContext
propagator and a BaggagePropagator, combines them into a CompositePropagator,
and registers it as the global propagator.  A single Inject() or Extract()
call then handles both W3C traceparent/tracestate headers and the baggage
header transparently.

When undefined, only an HttpTraceContext propagator is registered.  Baggage
must be handled explicitly: during extraction, a separate BaggagePropagator
is instantiated and its Extract() is called to merge baggage into the context.
During injection, the baggage content is read from the context and written to
the carrier as an additional header via Baggage::ToHeader().


5. OTELC_USE_MULTIPLE_PROCESSORS
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Default: defined.

Selects between a multi-processor provider architecture and a single-processor
provider architecture.

When defined, the tracer provider is created via TracerContext, which accepts
the full vector of span processors.  All processors configured in the YAML
file are active simultaneously, allowing telemetry to be exported to multiple
backends in parallel (e.g. OTLP/gRPC and OStream at the same time).  The
logger provider is created with the full vector of log record processors in
the same way.

When undefined, only the first processor in the vector is passed to the provider
constructor.  Any additional processors configured in YAML are silently ignored,
resulting in a single export pipeline per signal.


6. OTELC_USE_RUNTIME_CONTEXT
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Default: undefined.

Enables the OTel RuntimeContext mechanism for implicit parent span lookup,
carrier context retrieval, and metric exemplar correlation.

When defined, each span handle includes an additional scope field
(otel_nostd::shared_ptr<otel_trace::Scope>) that is created alongside the
span and pushes it into the OTel RuntimeContext as the active span.  This
has the following effects:

  * Parent span lookup: when start_span_with_options() is called without an
    explicit parent_span or parent_context, the current context is obtained
    from RuntimeContext::GetCurrent() instead of constructing an empty context.
    New spans automatically become children of the currently active span.

  * Carrier extraction: extract_text_map() and extract_http_headers() use
    RuntimeContext::GetCurrent() as the base context for propagator extraction
    instead of an empty context.

  * Metric context: update_instrument() and update_instrument_kv_n() pass
    RuntimeContext::GetCurrent() to the instrument's Add/Record call, enabling
    exemplar correlation with the active span.

When undefined, no scope is stored and RuntimeContext is not used.  An empty
otel_context::Context{} is substituted in all three cases above.  Parent-child
relationships must be established explicitly by passing parent_span or
parent_context to start_span_with_options().

This macro is undefined by default because the wrapper library's primary use
case (the HAProxy OTel filter) manages parent-child relationships explicitly
and does not rely on implicit context propagation.


7. OTELC_USE_INSTRUMENT_VALIDATOR
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Default: undefined (not user-configurable; defined outside OTELC_USER_CONFIG).

Enables instrument metadata validation when creating metric instruments.

When defined, otel_meter_create_instrument() calls
InstrumentMetaDataValidator::ValidateName(),
InstrumentMetaDataValidator::ValidateUnit(), and
InstrumentMetaDataValidator::ValidateDescription() before creating each
instrument.  These functions compile two std::regex objects on every call.

When undefined, the validation is skipped entirely and instrument names, units,
and descriptions are passed through without checking.

This macro is intentionally kept undefined because the std::regex construction
on every otel_meter_create_instrument() call causes a severe performance
penalty.  It is provided solely for development-time validation and should not
be enabled in production builds.


8. Custom configuration
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

To override the defaults, define OTELC_USER_CONFIG before configuration.h is
included (typically via a compiler flag) and provide the desired set of macro
definitions:

  CXXFLAGS="-DOTELC_USER_CONFIG               \
            -DOTELC_USE_THREAD_SHARED_HANDLE  \
            -DOTELC_USE_STATIC_HANDLE         \
            -DOTELC_USE_COMPOSITE_PROPAGATOR"

Any macro not explicitly defined in the custom configuration is left undefined.
The OTELC_USER_CONFIG guard prevents the default block from executing, giving
full control over which features are enabled.
